<div id="review_3245738791" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3245738791" />
    <a title="Edgarr Alien Pooh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh"><img alt="Edgarr Alien Pooh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1585112748p2/111745799.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3245738791?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edgarr Alien Pooh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edgarr Alien Pooh" href="/user/show/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh">Edgarr Alien Pooh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3245738791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1982267354683826581">We are all familiar with Twain’s major works like Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer but this book is Twain in an almost unrecognisable guise. Far from the banks of the great Mississippi River this tale takes place in Austria. One of the last pieces of writing that he finished, it was published posthumously.<br/>What appears to be a cleverly written snipe at standard religions, a mysterious man appears in town and performs trickery and magic, helping out some of the locals while befriending a group of three bo</span>
  <span id="freeText1982267354683826581" style="display:none">We are all familiar with Twain’s major works like Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer but this book is Twain in an almost unrecognisable guise. Far from the banks of the great Mississippi River this tale takes place in Austria. One of the last pieces of writing that he finished, it was published posthumously.<br />What appears to be a cleverly written snipe at standard religions, a mysterious man appears in town and performs trickery and magic, helping out some of the locals while befriending a group of three boys. The stranger goes by the name of Satan and he seems to share some of the talents which have been attributed to Christ over the years. He has a penchant for reading non verbalised thoughts and reading the future demise of townsfolk.<br />Twain appears to delight in the mockery of faith and I therefore would not recommend this book to anyone who holds faith dear. He casts Satan as the learned master, the trusted confidant of the boys and sets out to prove the fallibilities of the human race and in doing so casts dispersions on God and our perception of reality.<br />I found this book fun but it really seems to be a love/hate relationship with readers. Perhaps, I may argue, it is the beliefs of the reader that cast the opinion and not the book being read as a mere tale of fiction?<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1982267354683826581" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

