  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_673172089" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/673172089" />
    <a title="Sam Strong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16852513-sam-strong"><img alt="Sam Strong" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/673172089?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam Strong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam Strong" href="/user/show/16852513-sam-strong">Sam Strong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer673172089" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17199729546204990145">For those of you who view Mark Twain as a humorist, &quot;The Mysterious Stranger&quot; can come as quite the surprise. Written later in life, this book demonstrates Twain&apos;s lack of faith in the human race by presenting a character named Satan. He claims not to be the one Satan we all think of; instead, he says that he is &quot;the&quot; Satan&apos;s nephew. But that doesn&apos;t stop him from winning the friendship of three boys, including protagonist Theodor. Satan showers them with gifts and shows them miracles, then proc</span>
  <span id="freeText17199729546204990145" style="display:none">For those of you who view Mark Twain as a humorist, "The Mysterious Stranger" can come as quite the surprise. Written later in life, this book demonstrates Twain's lack of faith in the human race by presenting a character named Satan. He claims not to be the one Satan we all think of; instead, he says that he is "the" Satan's nephew. But that doesn't stop him from winning the friendship of three boys, including protagonist Theodor. Satan showers them with gifts and shows them miracles, then proceeds to show his cruelty by destroying a village of clay people that the boys had helped him make. This pattern of generosity and cruelty continues throughout the text, continuing on for many years as Satan comes and goes from the village. All the while, Satan accuses Theodor and the human race of not understanding his actions and being the ones who are needlessly cruel.<br /><br />This is one of the greatest pieces of literature I have ever read. It's dark, thought-provoking, and mind-bending. You frequently find yourself listening to Satan and internalizing his words, even though you know in your head you can't trust him. I highly recommend it to everyone, regardless of who they are or what their literary tastes are.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17199729546204990145" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review673172089">
